      <h3>Add-Ons</h3>
      <p>Available on any plan: extra chatbot ($10/mo), extra 1,000 message credits ($10/mo), extra 5M characters storage ($10/mo), remove branding ($29/mo or $290/yr), custom domain ($49/mo or $490/yr).</p>

      <h3>Message Credit System</h3>
      <p>Each chatbot response consumes message credits. Standard models (Gemini 2.5 Flash, GPT-5 Mini) use 1 credit per response. Advanced models consume more: GPT-4o, GPT-4.1, GPT-5.2, and Gemini 2.5 Pro use 5 credits; Claude 4.5 Sonnet uses 10 credits. This means the effective cost per conversation varies significantly depending on which model the chatbot uses.</p>

      <div class="callout info">
        <strong>Research note:</strong> The pricing credit box on the FastBots.ai website lists "GPT-5.2" while the FAQ lists "GPT-5" — these appear as different model references. Similarly, "Claude 4 Sonnet" (5 credits in FAQ) and "Claude 4.5 Sonnet" (10 credits in credit box) are documented separately but inconsistently across the site. This creates some ambiguity about which models are currently available.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="design">
      <h2>Platform &amp; Build Quality</h2>
      <p>FastBots.ai is a cloud-hosted SaaS platform. There is no self-hosted or on-premises option. All configuration happens through a web dashboard, and chatbots are deployed via an embeddable JavaScript widget or platform-specific integrations.</p>

      <h3>Technology Architecture</h3>
      <p>The platform connects to third-party LLM providers (OpenAI, Anthropic, Google) via their APIs. Uploaded training data is not used to train these underlying models — the FAQ confirms API-only access and links to OpenAI's enterprise privacy policy. Data is stored on SOC 2 and GDPR-compliant infrastructure with military-grade encryption, according to vendor statements.</p>

      <h3>Knowledge Ingestion</h3>
      <p>The web crawler is a notable component. The FAQ describes it as capable of handling JavaScript-rendered sites and active firewalls, which is relevant for businesses with modern single-page applications or security-hardened websites. Beyond websites, the platform accepts document uploads, Google Sheets, and YouTube video URLs (which it processes for transcript content).</p>

      <h3>Supported LLMs</h3>
      <p>Based on the captured pricing page and FAQ, FastBots.ai supports the following models:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>OpenAI:</strong> GPT-4o, GPT-4o Mini, GPT-4.1, GPT-4.1 Mini, GPT-4.1 Nano, o3, o4 Mini, GPT-5, GPT-5.2*, GPT-5 Mini, GPT-5 Nano</li>
        <li><strong>Anthropic:</strong> Claude 4.5 Sonnet, Claude 4 Sonnet, Claude 3.5 Haiku</li>
        <li><strong>Google:</strong> Gemini 2.0 Flash, Gemini 2.5 Flash, Gemini 2.5 Pro</li>
      </ul>
      <p><small>* GPT-5.2 appears in the pricing credit box but not in the FAQ model list — see model documentation note above.</small></p>

      <h3>Security &amp; Compliance</h3>
      <p>Vendor-claimed certifications include SOC 2 readiness and GDPR compliance. The site footer links to a Data Processing Agreement (DPA). Platform-level controls include domain whitelisting, password-protected chatbots, and rate limiting. HIPAA compliance is not mentioned in any documentation reviewed.</p>

      <h3>Visual Appeal &amp; Trust Signals</h3>
      <p>The homepage presents a clean, modern design with consistent branding. Trust signals are prominent: notable customer logos (Royal Caribbean, Holiday Inn, major universities), Stripe payment processing, and SOC 2/GDPR claims. Customer testimonials from six international small-business owners are displayed, suggesting a geographically diverse user base. The platform describes itself as having "almost daily" updates and maintains a public roadmap at roadmap.fastbots.ai for user feature voting.</p>
    </section>

